In Apache Spark, a DataFrame is a distributed collection of data organized into named columns, 
similar to a table in a relational database, with a defined schema and built-in optimizations for efficient processing.

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession

spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("DFExample").getOrCreate()

data = [("Alice", 25), ("Bob", 30)]
df = spark.createDataFrame(data, ["name", "age"])
df.show()
df.printSchema()

2. 
👉 Core Definition
n Apache Spark, both DataFrame and Dataset are distributed collections of data, but the key difference is that DataFrames are untyped and
provide a generic row-based structure, while Datasets are strongly typed and offer compile-time type safety using encoders.
DataFrames are essentially Datasets of type Row and are widely used in PySpark due to simplicity, whereas Datasets are mainly used in Scala/Java
for type-safe operations

In Apache Spark:

DataFrame → distributed data with schema (columns), but untyped (Row-based)
Dataset → distributed data with schema + type safety (strongly typed objects)
🧠 What “typed vs untyped” actually means

🔹 DataFrame (Untyped)
Data is accessed as generic Row
Errors happen at runtime
df.select("age")  # if column doesn't exist → runtime error

👉 Spark doesn’t validate structure at compile time

🔹 Dataset (Typed) — (Scala/Java only)
Data is mapped to case classes / objects
Errors caught at compile time
case class Person(name: String, age: Int)

val ds = spark.createDataset(Seq(Person("Alice", 25)))
ds.map(p => p.age)  // type-safe

👉 Compiler checks correctness before execution

